39. when request comes who will pick up first land balancer or api gateway 
    the Load Balancer almost always picks up the request first. Think of it as a two-layer entry system: the Load Balancer handles the "physical" traffic,
    and the API Gateway handles the "logical" routing and security for your microservices.

    The Typical Flow
        1. User Request: A user hits api.example.com.
        2. Load Balancer (Layer 4 or 7): This is the "Front Door." It receives the raw traffic. Its job is to distribute high volumes of incoming requests across multiple
            instances of your Gateway to ensure high availability.
        3. API Gateway: Once the Load Balancer hands off the request, the Gateway looks inside the request. It checks for a JWT token, validates the API key, and 
            decides which specific microservice (e.g., your "Interact City" configuration service) should receive it.
